            "> Repatriated North Koreans</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/seoul-repatriation-efforts-north-korea-communication.jpg" alt="The repatriation efforts were complicated by North Korean leader Kim Jong-un‚Äôs decision to cut inter-Korean communication lines" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i> The repatriation efforts were complicated by North Korean leader Kim Jong-un‚Äôs decision to cut inter-Korean communication lines. Credits: AP Photo </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Earlier this year, South Korea rescued six fishermen who drifted into their waters from North Korea - two in March in the Yellow Sea and four more in May in the East Sea. In a recent diplomatic move, South Korea has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-repatriated-the-fishermen" target="_blank">repatriated the fishermen</a> to their homeland on a wooden boat.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The conspiracy:</strong> Human rights <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-advocates-doubted" target="_blank">advocates doubted</a> the fishermen‚Äôs consent, saying that the UN Refugee Agency or other UN agencies in Seoul should have verified their wishes.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> Unlike his predecessors, President Lee Jae-myung seeks cooperation with North Korea and wants to revive inter-Korean dialogue. His recent <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-suspension-of-loudspeaker" target="_blank">suspension of loudspeaker</a> propaganda at the border, as well as his efforts to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-seek-china-s-mediation" target="_blank">seek China's mediation</a> for the denuclearization of the peninsula, highlight his intent for lasting peace in the region.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> Meanwhile, South Korea, the US, and the allies fear that Russia might provide Pyongyang with nuclear technology in return for the soldiers they sent to fight Russia‚Äôs war in Ukraine. </p>
        </mj-text>
