              margin-top: 2px !important;
            "> Trump‚Äôs BRICS issue</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>Summary: Trump is concerned about the BRICS‚Äôs anti-American agenda and looks to Africa for trade and mineral resources.</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> President Trump threatened an additional 10% tariff on countries that back BRICS‚Äôs anti-American policies. He warned the bloc against <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-undermining-the-us-currency" target="_blank">undermining the US currency</a> by promoting local currencies, which threatens America‚Äôs economic leadership. While these tariffs are lower than the 100% duties he promised in January, Trump insists they are necessary for protecting the dollar as the world‚Äôs reserve currency.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The reality:</strong> While the BRICS is focused on de-dollarization, the actual economic footprint remains minimal. Intra-BRICS trade makes up for 3% global trade, or around $1T. This doesn‚Äôt pose an immediate threat to the dollar, as 90% of global transactions and 59% of foreign exchange reserves still use US currency. Meanwhile, the BRICS-led New Development Bank has been cautious and lacks the strategic vision to rival Western institutions. The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-analysis-h1-10-ideological-differences" target="_blank">ideological differences</a> between states further complicate their progress.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The development:</strong> Trump understands the growing influence of BRICS and has recently begun a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-analysis-h1-11-three-day-summit" target="_blank">three-day summit</a> with five African nations to gain early influence. He emphasized a ‚Äútrade, not aid‚Äù approach and views these partnerships as key to securing a US gateway to critical minerals in Africa.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
