              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">What is Boris Yeltsin‚Äôs legacy? </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/boris-yeltsin-lost-fingers-hand-grenade-history.jpg" alt="Rebellious even as a youth, Boris Yeltsin lost two fingers while playing with a hand grenade" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>Rebellious even as a youth, Boris Yeltsin lost two fingers while playing with a hand grenade. Credits: History</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> On July 10th, 1991, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-foundations-h1-17-boris-yeltsin" target="_blank">Boris Yeltsin</a> became the first president of Russia following the collapse of the Soviet Union. His presidency was marked by political and economic reforms. He pursued privatization, lifted market value controls, and opened Russia‚Äôs economy to global markets. He also helped expand media liberty and political pluralism during the early years of his presidency.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The context:</strong> Yeltsin took power during a turbulent time. The collapse of the Soviet Union left the region plagued by rising crime, social instability, and economic turmoil. His ‚Äú<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-shock-therapy" target="_blank">shock therapy</a>‚Äù approach to liberalizing the economy helped Russia transition to an open market, but it also triggered hyperinflation, mass unemployment, and public discontent.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> In 1993, tensions between Yeltsin and the Russian parliament escalated to a constitutional crisis, as Yeltsin attempted to dissolve the parliament, which in turn tried to impeach him. Then, many people, including supporters of the parliament, barricaded themselves in the White House (the Russian parliament building). After negotiations failed, Yeltsin ordered <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-jul-25-foundations-h1-19-tanks-to-shell-the-white-house" target="_blank">tanks to shell the White House</a>, a move that deepened tensions but consolidated executive power. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The legacy:</strong> Domestically, he is remembered for both opening Russia to democratic principles and unleashing social chaos. The ineffective privatization led to the concentration of wealth among a small number of individuals, while many Russians fell into poverty. His desire for political centralization paved the way for a more authoritarian rule of his successor, Vladimir Putin.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
